4 Part V. Equity Participation Investment Program.
5 [5–549.] 5–538.
6 (a) In this part the following words have the meanings indicated.
7 (b) (1) “Enterprise” means a business entity proposing to carry on a business
8 in the State that meets the requirements of [§ 5–526] § 5–521 of this subtitle.
9 (2) “Enterprise” includes:
10 (i) a sole proprietorship;
11 (ii) a partnership;
12 (iii) A LIMITED LIABILITY CORPORATION;
13 (IV) a limited partnership;
14 [(iv)] (V) a corporation; or
15 [(v)] (VI) a joint venture.
16 (c) “Equity participation financing” includes investment or guaranty of
17 investment in an enterprise.
18 (d) “Existing business” means a business whose board of directors or owners
19 approve the sale of the business to an enterprise receiving equity participation financing.
20 (e) [“Fund” means the Equity Participation Investment Program Fund.
21 (f)] “Program” means the Equity Participation Investment Program.
22 [(g)] (F) “Qualified security” means:
23 (1) a note, bond, debenture, or other evidence of indebtedness;
24 (2) stock or other form of equity participation;
25 (3) a certificate of interest or participation in a profit–sharing agreement;

44 HOUSE BILL 898
1 (4) an investment contract;
2 (5) a certificate of deposit for a security;
3 (6) a certificate of interest or participation in a patent or patent application
4 or in royalty or other payments under a patent or patent application; or
5 (7) an interest or instrument commonly known as a “security” or a
6 certificate for, receipt for, guaranty of, or option, warrant, or right to subscribe to or
7 purchase a qualified security.
8 [(h)] (G) “Small business” means a business that is classified as a small business
9 under the U.S. Small Business Administration size standards.
10 [5–550.] 5–539.
11 (a) The General Assembly finds that:
12 (1) small businesses have proven to be a fast growing and reliable form of
13 successful business expansion and successful new business creation;
14 (2) small businesses play a major role in the economy of the State and have
15 been a continuing source of increasing tax revenues and job opportunities;
16 (3) the growth of small businesses should be encouraged and should be an
17 integral part of the State’s economic development effort;
18 (4) socially or economically disadvantaged individuals often lack adequate
19 capital and are unable to obtain financing from financial institutions or venture capital
20 firms to begin and develop a small business, or to purchase an existing business; and
21 (5) promoting the creation and viability of small businesses and the
22 purchase of existing businesses by socially or economically disadvantaged individuals is in
23 the public interest.
24 (b) The purposes of the Equity Participation Investment Program are to:
25 (1) encourage and help socially or economically disadvantaged individuals
26 to create and develop small businesses and acquire existing businesses in the State; and
27 (2) assist small businesses that, because they do not meet the established
28 credit criteria of financial institutions, cannot obtain adequate business financing on
29 reasonable terms through normal financing channels.
30 [5–551.] 5–540.

